shortDescriptions.default.value: Bai Mu Dan Tea White Peony is the most famous Chinese white tea that grows in the north of Fujian, Mount WI, where the unique Big White Tea variety of Da Bai Cha tea tree is located.
descriptions.default.value:
Bai Mu Dan Tea White Peony is the most famous Chinese white tea that grows in the north of Fujian, Mount WI, where the unique Big White Tea variety of Da Bai Cha tea tree is located.

For the production of Bai Mu Dan White Peony tea, only young tea buds and two upper leaves are harvested. The tea leaf is not twisted, it remains in its natural form, the leaf is slightly warmed up and dried in the sun, and then only dried. Within a couple of days, the tea dries and ferments, due to which new compounds appear that are so useful for our body.

The taste of this tea is delicate, elegant and deep slightly with a sweet honey-nut-flower bouquet. The aroma is floral-fruity, sweet and fragrant. A fresh, long, sweet, fruity finish is felt. The color of brewed tea is light golden.

White Tea Bai Mu Dan gives a refreshing and disinfecting effect, according to Chinese scientists, it removes heat well, improves emotional state, at the same time relaxes and tones, creating a feeling of pleasant comfort, lightness and peace. Great for drinking tea in the warm and hot season. This is a rather rare and tasty tea; it has gained a reputation as aristocrats and intellectuals. It should not be combined with food.

This tea is useful for the complete cleansing of the body, has a rejuvenating effect. Due to its unique properties, its extracts are part of the line of cosmetics for face and body care. Due to its antimicrobial effect, it is used to prevent caries. Bai Mu Dan also improves cholesterol metabolism, slows down skin aging, and helps rejuvenate the whole body. Thus, science confirms the statement of the Chinese emperors, who called white tea a drink of immortality.
Country.name: China

names.default.value: Zhen Shan Xiao Zhong (Small bushes from Zhen Shan mountain) or Lapsang Souchong_1
shortDescriptions.default.value: Zhen Shan Xiao Zhong is the famous red Chinese tea that grows in the north of Fujian province, on the slopes of Mount Zhen Shan. It was Lapsang Souchong tea that particularly appealed to Europeans and determined the future development of tea making in the Southeast region of China.
descriptions.default.value:
Zhen Shan Xiao Zhong is the famous red Chinese tea that grows in the north of Fujian province, on the slopes of Mount Zhen Shan. It was Lapsang Souchong tea that particularly appealed to Europeans and determined the future development of tea making in the Southeast region of China.

Collection of tea bush leaves begins in June. The processing of collected tea takes about a day, begins very early in the morning and until the deepest night. As raw materials, use 2-3 large tea leaves, which immediately after collection wither. In the manufacture of Lapsang Souchong tea, the first wilting in sunlight is used. Then the tea is curled. After twisting, the tea is poured into baskets, where fermentation takes place. This is done near the fire or over the hearth to increase the temperature of the tea. Within 6-8 hours, it warms up until the taste and smell of greenery come out of it. As a result of this procedure, the leaf surface acquires a red-brown color. During drying and roasting, the tea is heated on pine wood (roots of Chinese spruce). As a result, tea acquires a resinous pine smell.

The color of the infusion is red-burgundy. In addition to a peculiar smoked flavor, Zhen Shan Xiao Zhong has a sweet taste, with a touch of honey pear and dates. The finish is lingering with an aromatic finale in which you can hear a harmonious symphony of floral keys.

Red tea is especially good in the cold season. It is recommended to use after prolonged physical effort in the cold: for example, mountain climbing, after skiing and so on.

The actions of this tea are diverse: it tones, has a good warming effect, improves well-being, creates a feeling of comfort. Systemic use of Zhen Shan Shan Xiao Zhong helps to eliminate carcinogens and toxins from the body, boosts immunity, improves blood condition, and improves digestion.

descriptions.default.value:
Qimun is one of China's most revered teas. The name translates from Chinese as "Great Gate". This tea grows in eastern China in Anhui province, in the area of Huan Shan Mountain (Yellow Mountain). For the preparation of Kimuna, only a tea bud and two or three leaves are used. Unlike standard technologies for preparing red tea, after roasting, the tea leaf is additionally cut into pieces of 6-8 mm in length, so the teas of this variety look somewhat smaller than other classic Chinese teas.

The taste of Kimun is rich and rich, in the world of teas this tea is called Burgundy wine. The bouquet is dominated by fruit (prunes and apricot) and coniferous notes. Sometimes smoky and floral notes appear, especially an orchid. The color of the infusion is saturated, red-brown. Serving it is recommended for spicy spicy dishes, or for desserts. This tea is often chosen as a gift to high-ranking guests of China.

Having bought red Kimon tea, you are guaranteed to improve: the condition of the gums and teeth, the gastrointestinal tract, the condition of the kidneys and mood (tea tones, relieves stress, fatigue).

names.default.value: Ancient Shu Pu'er Cake Vintage 2009 | Special Grade_1
descriptions.default.value:
This vintage tea consists of aged shu pu'er that is compressed into a cake and packed in traditional bamboo leaf bundles called a tong. This reserve pu'er tea is released only when it is ready. A deep garnet infusion with a dense, opaque liquor bears a mellow sweetness that drinks remarkably smooth with a rich earth body.

There are two types of Pu'er tea: Sheng (raw, green) and Shu (ripe, dark). Both originate from a rustic sun-dried green tea called Shaiqing. Shu Pu'er is made by pile-fermenting Shaiqing teas over a period of 85-120 days. Ancient Pu'er Palace is our top grade of Shu Pu'er, and is made using leaves picked from ancient tea trees that are hundreds of years old.

Like fine wine, Pu'er tea has the ability to be aged and released in vintages. Young Shu Pu'er teas (2-3 years) typically have an assertive body and bold strength. The body and mouthfeel become richer and more integrated as the Shu Pu'er continues to age from 4-8 years.

descriptions.default.value: This exclusive Pu'er blend originates from the remote Dai, Lahu, and Wa ethnic mountain villages in southern Yunnan Province, where heirloom broad leaf tea varietals have developed a complexity from centuries of seed propagation. Ancient Pu'er Classic comprises multiple vintages resulting in a uniquely bold flavor profile with a body as deep as its history. This Shu Pu'er is notable for its notes of earthy sweetness, hints of cocoa, and a woodsy, aromatic finish. The very best in everyday organic Pu'er.

descriptions.default.value:
A nice intro to this classic, uniquely Chinese tea. When rinsed and steeped 30 seconds, it is slightly earthy and medium-bodied with a very slight floral/sweet note. Good for multiple steepings.

This wonderful tea was made by Mr. Fu Bing Bing, who has been specializing in shou puers in Puer City, Yunnan for more than a decade.

The flavor of all puer teas evolves over time. This is because there are naturally occurring active micro-organisms in the leaf that over time change the aroma and the flavor of the tea. All dark teas (including puer) can be wonderful when they are "young" ie, less than 2 years old. Each year after that the flavor will get a little richer, deeper, more complex. Many people store dark teas, particularly puers, for years before drinking, because they really enjoy that more fully evolved, more complex, stronger flavor. So feel free to experiment with steeping times and storage times to find the best method to get the flavor you want from your dark tea.
